@REM==============================================================================

@node "FIM" "FIM - FAME Interface Module"

                          @{b}FIM - FAME Interface Module
                         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

FIM is the FAME Interface Module and defines the FAME Door standard.

This includes the Door Message structure, the command layout, the commands
themselves and also DoorHelp.

This also includes the @{"Rules and GuideLines" link "Rules"}.
@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Rules" "Rules and GuideLines"

                             @{b}Rules and GuideLines
                            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

There are serveral Rules and GuideLines.

We still have to work some of them completely out.

Now follows a short overview.

@{b}@{u}FIM - FAME Interface Module Rules and GuideLines are:@{ub}@{uu}

 - Observance of the original Commodore Amiga GuideLines such as SytleGuide.

 - No hacks and bad code.

 - Usage of the FAME.library for allocations via FAMEAllocObject.

   You *HAVE* to allocate the DoorMessage structure with FAMEAllocObject()
   else your Doors may crash the System on later FAME versions!

 - Usage of the FAME.library when ever possible.

 - No endless lockings of resources such as FAMESemaphore.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "DoorHelp" "DoorHelp standard"

                               @{b}DoorHelp standard
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The idea of DoorHelp is to give FAME Door programmers a tool to build into
their door to provide a standardized online help based on AmigaGuide.

DoorHelp will use standard AmigaGuide files.

A door can install as many Help.guides in as many different languages as it
supports. They will be installed into a directory in 'FAME:DoorHelp/' where
the assign 'DoorHelp:' will point to.
In 'DoorHelp:' there are language dirs such as 'English/' and 'Deutsch/'.

DoorHelp shall be called by a Door via a FIM command where it tells FAME
the guide name and the node in the guide it wants to display to the
user if a user calls help.

@{"MainPart" link "MainPart.guide/Main"} will build up a path to the guide depending on 'DoorHelp:' and
the user's selected language if available. If the guide doesn't exist
in the language the user has configured the default language 'English'
will be used. In this case the path will look like:
'DoorHelp:english/MyDoorHelp.guide'

FAMEDoorHelp will be also a door and will be able to find out if the user
connected locally (normally the SysOp) or if it was called from the serial.

If local 'FAMEDoorHelp.FIM' will give the path to AmigaGuide which will
open the guide on the @{"MainPart" link "MainPart.guide/Main"} public screen.

If it's used from serial, FAMEDoorHelp will interpret the guide itself.
The user will be able to walk through the guide via kyeboard and cursor
keys.

@endnode

